Topic: Concurrency Control (Distributed Systems)

1️⃣ Real Problem (Why Concurrency Control Exists)

Imagine BookMyShow seat booking.

Seat status:

Seat A1 = FREE

3 users ek hi time pe click karte hain:

User1 → Book
User2 → Book
User3 → Book

Flow:

Step1: Read seat status
Step2: If FREE → Book
Step3: Update DB

Parallel execution:

User1 read → FREE
User2 read → FREE
User3 read → FREE

All update:

Seat → BOOKED

Result:

User1 success
User2 success
User3 success

🚨 Same seat 3 log ko mil gaya

Ye hi hai concurrency problem.

2️⃣ Local Solution (Single Machine)

Agar single server ho:

synchronized block

Example Java:

synchronized(bookSeat){
   if(seat == FREE){
       seat = BOOKED;
   }
}

Now execution:

User1 enters critical section
User2 waits
User3 waits

Result:

User1 success
User2 fail
User3 fail

Correct.

3️⃣ Problem in Distributed System

But production system:

Load Balancer
   |
   |------ Server1
   |------ Server2
   |------ Server3

Requests:

User1 → Server1
User2 → Server2
User3 → Server3

Each server has its own memory.

synchronized works only inside one JVM

❌ It cannot coordinate across machines.

So we need:

Distributed Concurrency Control
4️⃣ Tools Used

Three core concepts:

1️⃣ Transactions
2️⃣ Locks
3️⃣ Isolation levels
5️⃣ Transactions (ACID)

Example bank transfer.

A = 100
B = 50

Transfer 20.

Steps:

Debit A → 80
Credit B → 70

If crash happens between steps:

A = 80
B = 50

Money lost.

Transaction ensures:

Either both succeed
or none

Rollback happens.

6️⃣ Database Locks

Two types.

Shared Lock (Read Lock)

Multiple readers allowed.

T1 → read
T2 → read
T3 → read

But no writes allowed.

Exclusive Lock (Write Lock)

Only one transaction allowed.

T1 → write
T2 → blocked
T3 → blocked
7️⃣ Isolation Levels (How Strict DB Is)

There are 4 levels.

1 Read Uncommitted
2 Read Committed
3 Repeatable Read
4 Serializable

Higher level = more safety = less concurrency.

8️⃣ Problems These Solve
Dirty Read

Transaction reads uncommitted data.

Example:

T1 updates price → 100 → 200
T2 reads 200
T1 rollback → price back to 100

T2 read wrong data.

Non-Repeatable Read

Same query gives different result.

T1 read price = 100
T2 update price = 200
T1 read again → 200

Same transaction different value.

Phantom Read

Number of rows change.

Example:

Query:

SELECT * FROM seats WHERE price < 500

First result:

10 rows

Another transaction inserts row.

Second result:

11 rows
9️⃣ Isolation Level Summary
Level	Dirty Read	Non-Repeatable	Phantom
Read Uncommitted	❌ allowed	❌	❌
Read Committed	✅ solved	❌	❌
Repeatable Read	✅	✅	❌
Serializable	✅	✅	✅
🔟 Two Ways to Handle Concurrency

Two main strategies:

1️⃣ Optimistic Concurrency Control
2️⃣ Pessimistic Concurrency Control
1️⃣1️⃣ Optimistic Concurrency Control

Idea:

Conflicts are rare

So:

Don't lock
Check later

Used in:

High scalability systems
How It Works

Add version column.

seat_id | status | version
A1      | FREE   | 1

Two users read:

User1 → version 1
User2 → version 1

User1 updates:

UPDATE seat
SET status='BOOKED', version=2
WHERE id=A1 AND version=1

Success.

User2 tries:

WHERE version=1

But DB version now:

version = 2

Update fails.

User2 retry.

So conflict detected at commit time.

1️⃣2️⃣ Pessimistic Concurrency Control

Idea:

Conflicts likely

So:

Lock resource immediately

Example:

SELECT * FROM seat
FOR UPDATE

Now row locked.

Other transactions:

must wait

Used in:

Banking systems
inventory systems
1️⃣3️⃣ Deadlock Problem

Example:

Transaction1:

lock A
then lock B

Transaction2:

lock B
then lock A

Result:

T1 waiting for B
T2 waiting for A

Deadlock.

DB resolves by killing one transaction.

1️⃣4️⃣ Optimistic vs Pessimistic
Feature	Optimistic	Pessimistic
Locking	No	Yes
Concurrency	High	Low
Deadlock	No	Possible
Use case	Rare conflicts	Frequent conflicts
1️⃣5️⃣ Real Systems Use
Optimistic

Used in:

REST APIs
microservices
high scale systems

Example:

version column
ETag
CAS
Pessimistic

Used in:

bank transfers
inventory deduction
seat booking
🧠 Final Mental Model

Concurrency solutions:

Application Level
   |
   |-- synchronized / mutex
   |
Database Level
   |
   |-- optimistic concurrency
   |-- pessimistic locking
⭐ Most Important Interview Answer

If interviewer asks:

How will you handle concurrency in BookMyShow?

Answer:

Use pessimistic locking

SELECT seat
FOR UPDATE

OR

Use optimistic locking with version column